{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aeffb660-5fbf-47d0-b12e-ce95678671c2","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the **currently recorded versions** of your workloads. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but does **not** upgrade them to match a newer SDK.\n\nSince your issue started after an SDK update, your workloads need to be **upgraded**, not just reinstalled:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, verify the MAUI workload is present with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0552dbf1-b204-4ae1-88cf-0b873f840224","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"9BCA:180DF7:5F53CF1:6A85438:69EC0DE8"},"id":"d2801091-9574-4f5f-ae1c-5ff8593c00e8","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:42:23.684Z","parentId":"66dbe705-3520-43f8-a33c-58d4c4efe293"}
